WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.500
I'm going to talk a little bit about GPRC5D-related adverse events, and particularly about the

00:00:06.500 --> 00:00:10.380
management of taste changes, and talk a little bit about some of the work that we've been

00:00:10.380 --> 00:00:15.760
doing at J&J with many of you in the community trying to understand this a little bit better.

00:00:16.160 --> 00:00:19.920
Before I jump into it, just a disclosure, I'm an employer of Johnson & Johnson.

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:22.780
I head up the Global Medical Affairs Organization at J&J.

00:00:23.720 --> 00:00:28.340
So let's talk a little bit about GPRC5D-related targeted therapies for a second, and Rita

00:00:28.340 --> 00:00:30.280
and others really talked about this really elegantly.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.700
This idea of targeting GPRC5D, it's relatively novel.

00:00:34.920 --> 00:00:39.940
It's a target that J&J had really identified and brought forward, and we were really doing

00:00:39.940 --> 00:00:41.120
that for a number of reasons.

00:00:41.280 --> 00:00:46.920
One of those is really that idea that it doesn't have that expression across the entire B-cell

00:00:46.920 --> 00:00:47.560
lineage.

00:00:47.560 --> 00:00:51.700
And we thought that this was going to be really an important opportunity to target something

00:00:51.700 --> 00:00:56.060
where we had seen those traditional infectious risks with BCMA-targeting agents.

00:00:56.840 --> 00:00:57.980
We were really impressed.

00:00:58.100 --> 00:00:58.320
In terms of...

00:00:58.320 --> 00:01:01.380
In terms of the efficacy that we initially saw, really raising that bar.

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:07.020
I remember at ASH a couple of years ago, we talked about 60 was the new 20, but talcoidamab

00:01:07.020 --> 00:01:09.440
kind of broke that with a 70% response rate.

00:01:09.840 --> 00:01:14.560
And I think impressively, right, we still haven't seen the median overall survival in

00:01:14.560 --> 00:01:16.180
the original MONUMENTAL-1 study.

00:01:16.980 --> 00:01:23.180
But what we have seen are these adverse events, particularly related to targeting GPRC5D.

00:01:23.640 --> 00:01:28.300
Oral-related toxicities in particular, dyskousia, dry mouth, and you heard about some of the

00:01:28.300 --> 00:01:31.220
some of those in terms of also some of the skin toxicities, too.

00:01:32.480 --> 00:01:36.680
Now, one of the things that we have been thinking about from a J&J perspective is where can

00:01:36.680 --> 00:01:38.920
you use things like GPRC5D agents, right?

00:01:38.920 --> 00:01:43.940
You all saw the great data of MAJESTIC-3 at ASH, but there are other places that we have

00:01:43.940 --> 00:01:49.840
been working on developing talcoidamab in both the newly diagnosed setting with MAJESTIC-5,

00:01:49.840 --> 00:01:54.020
looking at that in combination to try to improve that induction before transplant.

00:01:54.820 --> 00:01:57.200
We've got the MAJESTIC-7 study that's ongoing looking at TANF.

00:01:57.200 --> 00:01:57.420
We've got the MAJESTIC-7 study that's ongoing looking at TANF.

00:01:57.420 --> 00:01:57.460
We've got the MAJESTIC-7 study that's ongoing looking at TANF.

00:01:57.460 --> 00:01:57.660
We've got the MAJESTIC-7 study that's ongoing looking at TANF.

00:01:57.660 --> 00:02:04.300
that TAL-DARA-REV versus the MYA regimen in that treatment ineligible setting.

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:08.680
We also have the AMBITION study, which I didn't put up here. And that's actually something

00:02:08.680 --> 00:02:13.700
worthwhile talking about because in the AMBITION study, we actually are using talquetamab before

00:02:13.700 --> 00:02:20.600
siltacel. So we are using a DVRD followed by a TAL-DARA before you go to siltacel. And we have

00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:25.400
a TAL-based regimen after siltacel as well. And we've got tons of translational work,

00:02:25.500 --> 00:02:28.620
correlative work in there. So those questions that we were talking about in terms of

00:02:28.620 --> 00:02:35.060
how could using a GPRC5 agent before a BCMA, we're going to answer a lot of those questions

00:02:35.060 --> 00:02:39.700
because there's tons of correlatives in there. I think it really become clear that using TAL

00:02:39.700 --> 00:02:44.560
potentially as a bridge before CARVIC-T is super successful. Karina was talking about this earlier.

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:48.780
If you can get these patients into a PR or a BETA, many of those adverse events that we're

00:02:48.780 --> 00:02:53.300
seeing are really mitigated to a significant degree. I think the data that Binod presented

00:02:53.340 --> 00:03:01.780
recently showing talquetamab before siltacel was very successful. Monumental 3, soon. You'll see

00:03:01.780 --> 00:03:06.300
those results really soon. And I think that'll help us understand how does TAL-DARA work versus

00:03:06.300 --> 00:03:11.760
TEC-DARA. We saw that TEC-DARA data and does POM add anything when you add it to that TAL-DARA

00:03:11.760 --> 00:03:17.660
regimen? TEC-TAL, what about that in that late line setting, those patients who've seen CD38

00:03:17.660 --> 00:03:23.020
or TAL-POM, we'll see that too. And we heard about the redirect study with TEC-TAL. So we've got a

00:03:23.180 --> 00:03:29.060
lot of GPRC5D-related regimens that are coming, and addressing this question about oral toxicities

00:03:29.060 --> 00:03:34.420
is going to be really important. But just to talk about, again, why we were thinking about GPRC5D,

00:03:34.720 --> 00:03:40.140
it was really because of this infection issue. We know that GPRC5D is only expressed really in

00:03:40.140 --> 00:03:45.500
those mature B cells, and that is something that we have seen quite regularly. We see lower rates

00:03:45.500 --> 00:03:50.080
of severe infections, lower overall rates of infections, and we see B cell recovery in these

00:03:50.080 --> 00:03:51.820
patients, which we think is particularly important.

00:03:53.020 --> 00:03:57.120
But we've seen these GPRC5-related toxicities. We've seen in many of the patients we get

00:03:57.120 --> 00:04:03.100
dyscusia. It happens very quickly, but we do see it resolve. But one of the questions that we're

00:04:03.100 --> 00:04:08.220
having is we really need to look at this in a more detailed and a more rigorous way, and that's why

00:04:08.220 --> 00:04:15.480
we went about designing a study called TALISMAN. We have seen it, this GPRC5-related toxicities too,

00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:20.200
in other agents. So it's not a TAL-QUERDIBAB issue per se, it's really more of a target issue.

00:04:20.860 --> 00:04:22.860
But what we've recently learned, and I'll tell you,

00:04:22.860 --> 00:04:27.900
this is a learning in the last year or so, is that we've really identified that there is

00:04:27.900 --> 00:04:35.960
in the mouth, in this cleft in the tongue, there is this von Ebner's gland. And in that von Ebner's

00:04:35.960 --> 00:04:43.260
gland, GPRC5D is present. And so really those dyscusia or those oral toxicities are really an

00:04:43.260 --> 00:04:52.700
on-target, but off-tumor GPRC5D-related oral toxicity. So we will see this with other GPRC5-

00:04:52.700 --> 00:04:58.140
related agents. So that is really the target. And the question is, is what does that presentation

00:04:58.140 --> 00:05:02.720
look like? How does that change over time? And what can we learn from that? Now we've seen a

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:07.080
lot of people doing lots of different things, good oral hygiene, lots of different things in terms of

00:05:07.080 --> 00:05:13.080
helping patients with the dysphagia and the dry mouth. And those things are working, but I think

00:05:13.080 --> 00:05:18.240
the question is, is what can we do to help prevent it or treat it? And what does that natural history

00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:22.540
look like? So we went about designing the TALISMAN study. This is a fully enrolled randomized face

00:05:22.540 --> 00:05:28.940
to study. We have group A, which is run contemporaneously with groups B, C, and D.

00:05:29.440 --> 00:05:34.140
And that's no prophylaxis. That's your regular treatment of those patients. So we can rigorously

00:05:34.140 --> 00:05:41.260
then compare prophylaxis versus no prophylaxis. So all three arms are complete. You'll see the

00:05:41.260 --> 00:05:46.940
data from arm A and B at EHA, hopefully, if they give us a presentation, knock wood,

00:05:47.420 --> 00:05:52.380
looking at dexamethasone. And then we've also got the oral vergabalin and the clompasin

00:05:52.380 --> 00:05:57.880
as well. Now, we also are intending to add a tacrolimus arm to this study too. And we're also

00:05:57.880 --> 00:06:01.980
going to study romantomic, because we know romantomic in itself, dual targeting of both

00:06:01.980 --> 00:06:08.580
BCMA and GPRC5D has a different binder. And we believe that this binder brings a differentiated

00:06:08.580 --> 00:06:13.140
toxicity profile, particularly around adverse events from an oral toxicity perspective.

00:06:13.860 --> 00:06:18.800
But what are we seeing or how did we design this? Listen, we're all using CTCA today,

00:06:18.800 --> 00:06:22.220
but what we did is we put two particular measures into

00:06:22.220 --> 00:06:27.980
this. This STTA measure is a very subjective patient orientated approach where the patient

00:06:27.980 --> 00:06:32.220
is really telling you, my taste hasn't changed. I've had some mild loss, moderate, severe,

00:06:32.220 --> 00:06:37.420
or complete. But the wet test is the key one. This is purely objective. It is not related to

00:06:37.420 --> 00:06:42.700
the physician or the patient. It is very objective in how it's done. And it allows

00:06:42.700 --> 00:06:47.660
us really independently assess that. And something I don't think I knew before this is that there are

00:06:47.660 --> 00:06:52.060
many different ways in which people taste. And so we can look at all those elements of taste

00:06:52.060 --> 00:06:57.740
as well to understand that. And so we've have those assessments in terms of the wet test,

00:06:57.740 --> 00:07:03.100
this STTA test as well. But I think one of the key things that we have come out with and found,

00:07:03.100 --> 00:07:09.100
and we presented these data, these preliminary data at ASH, is that we are seeing taste recovery

00:07:09.100 --> 00:07:14.940
within three months and more taste recovery within seven months. Now, I know there's a lot of

00:07:14.940 --> 00:07:20.860
speculation. Maybe that's related to changing from Q2 week to Q4 week, but we don't believe that's

00:07:20.860 --> 00:07:21.900
necessarily the case. And what we're trying to do is we're trying to figure out how we're going to

00:07:21.900 --> 00:07:25.500
do that. And one of the best ways to kind of look at that and think about that is looking at that

00:07:25.500 --> 00:07:32.220
change in taste changes over time. And what you see when you typically go to a Q4 week schedule,

00:07:32.220 --> 00:07:37.340
that taste change is already starting to come back. And we see that as you have this deep response,

00:07:37.340 --> 00:07:41.980
you see these taste changes. You see that very empirically with this wet test.

00:07:41.980 --> 00:07:47.020
And we hear from patients almost immediately at step-up doses, at first full dose, we're

00:07:47.020 --> 00:07:51.660
seeing those taste changes. But then we start to see at three months and six months the recovery of

00:07:51.740 --> 00:07:57.500
that. And this is really allowing us to understand those taste changes versus controls and versus

00:07:57.500 --> 00:08:00.940
those patients where we're going to be looking at those preventative therapies too.

00:08:00.940 --> 00:08:05.980
So we are hopeful that we can find something. We have also been looking at some biological

00:08:05.980 --> 00:08:10.380
correlives working with Boston Gene to try to really understand from an immune perspective,

00:08:10.380 --> 00:08:13.580
what is going on in the mouth? What is going on in those renal glands? What is

00:08:13.580 --> 00:08:18.300
happening in the salivary glands as well? Doing biopsies, looking at some immune profiling work,

00:08:18.300 --> 00:08:21.580
because we think that there may be some activity in terms of that immune

00:08:21.580 --> 00:08:28.140
response. And so we are hoping that we can start to see some engagement with that von Ebner receptor

00:08:28.140 --> 00:08:31.580
and that there's some bystander effects where you see these types of changes.

00:08:31.580 --> 00:08:35.980
But the good news is we're starting to see it recover. We're seeing that consistently. I think

00:08:35.980 --> 00:08:40.700
the question now is what can we do to approach that? And I think just from a J&J perspective,

00:08:40.700 --> 00:08:45.660
I was reflecting on the presentations from the very beginning of the meeting. And I was listening

00:08:45.660 --> 00:08:49.420
to Tom and everybody else talking about the progress we've made in multiple myeloma. We have

00:08:49.420 --> 00:08:51.420
made incredible progress. And it's actually quite amazing to hear us talking about cure,

00:08:51.420 --> 00:08:55.020
and being in Miami a couple of weeks ago, defining cure. It's amazing.

00:08:55.020 --> 00:08:59.420
But we also have to focus not on treatment, but also helping patients live and live well.

00:08:59.420 --> 00:09:05.160
That's so important because patients not living well, that doesn't work. And I know that in
